International Relations</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gpol"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gvbod"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gvcng"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets><DescTPC fid="de"><DescField fid="ipd">Parliament </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Singapore</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Parliament set to take a mid-year break </Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>SINGAPORE — After a marathon three-day sitting which saw 12 bills passed, Parliament is now set to take a mid-term break for the Government to take stock of its work over the last two-and-a-half years and map out its legislative agenda for the second half of its term.</Para><Para>Parliament is likely to be prorogued in the coming days, as Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong had set out the timeline last November, when he said that the legislature will be taking a mid-term break after the Budget.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Before it reconvenes, probably in May, a much-anticipated Cabinet reshuffle will take place, which will see Singapore’s next-generation leadership given heavier responsibilities.</Para><Para>In the reshuffle, Prime Minister Lee is expected to appoint more fourth generation (4G) leaders to helm their own ministries.</Para><Para>He had announced plans for the major Cabinet reshuffle as early as April last year, sparking speculation about who would become Singapore’s fourth PM.</Para><Para>Earlier this year, Emeritus Senior Minister Goh Chok Tong touched off more talk when he publicly expressed his hope that Mr Lee’s successor could be identified before the end of the year.</Para><Para>However, Mr Lee dampened speculation when he said it would take the 4G team “a bit longer” than nine months to pick a leader among themselves.</Para><Para>Noting that a strong team was in place and that the political transition would be done in “good time”, he added that the designation of his successor would not be “imminent” as that would depend on the dynamics between the younger leaders.</Para><Para>This keenly-watched reshuffle would be the fourth set of Cabinet changes since the start of the incumbent Government’s term from January 2016.</Para><Para>When the legislative body reconvenes, President Halimah Yacob will make her maiden address to the 13th Parliament.</Para><Para>The former Speaker of Parliament became the first woman and first Malay in 47 years to ascend to the highest office of the land last year, following changes to the Elected Presidency scheme were set in motion to ensure the political institution remains robust and effective.</Para><Para>In her address, she will set out the agenda for the second half of the Government’s term. These include economic restructuring, infrastructure investments, and enhancing social resilience through supporting young families and managing healthcare costs, for example.</Para><Para>Following that, the various ministries will present their addenda, and the House will debate these policies and programmes in its debate on the Motion of Thanks for the President’s Address.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field"></Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018. MediaCorp Press Ltd. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article">